Step 1:  Since $4-\sqrt{11}$ is a root of the polynomial $p(x)$, the other root must be its conjugate: $4+\sqrt{11}.$
 The quadratic polynomial with roots $4-\sqrt{11}$ and $4+\sqrt{11}$ can be expressed as: $p(x)=(x-(4-\sqrt{11}))(x-(4+\sqrt{11})).$
Step 2:  Expanding the above expression for $p(x)$ gives us $p(x)=x^2-8x+15.$
Step 3:
\begin{align*}
p(3)&=3^2-8\cdot3+15=9-24+15=-0,\\
p(4)&=4^2-8\cdot4+15=16-32+15=-1.
\end{align*}
Step 4:
\begin{align*}
\frac{p(3)}{p(4)}&=\frac{-0}{-1}\\
&=\boxed{0}
\end{align*}
